<methodology slug="diary-study-basics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Longitudinal method: participants self-record behaviors over days/weeks with in-the-moment context and evolving understanding.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>diary</tag>
      <tag>study</tag>
      <tag>longitudinal</tag>
      <tag>self-report</tag>
      <tag>experience</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>research</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Diary Study Basics</title>
    <summary>A longitudinal research method where participants self-record behaviors, thoughts, and contexts in the moment or shortly after, over days or weeks. Three variants: interval-contingent (fixed schedule), event-contingent (triggered by occurrence), and signal-contingent (random prompts). Each entry captures when, where, what happened, how the participant felt, and their interpretation.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Lab studies capture a single snapshot; diary studies reveal how behavior evolves over time, what context shapes usage, and when habits form. The method produces in-the-moment data that retrospective interviews cannot recover — participants' recall of "typical" behavior is systematically inaccurate after 48 hours. Diary studies capture real-world context that lab conditions eliminate and tracking of how user understanding evolves from novice to proficient.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Studying behavior that unfolds over days or weeks (onboarding journeys, habit formation, multi-device patterns).</item>
        <item>Capturing real-world context (location, mood, environment) that lab conditions eliminate.</item>
        <item>Tracking how user understanding evolves from novice to proficient.</item>
        <item>Pre-purchase or high-consideration journeys where each touchpoint matters.</item>
        <item>Validating retention drop-off hypotheses by following individual usage trajectories.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Need findings in under two weeks — minimum useful diary period is 7-14 days.</item>
        <item>Single isolated event with no context dependency — a post-event interview is faster and cheaper.</item>
        <item>Sensitive personal contexts (mental health, finances) without ethics review — continuous self-documentation feels surveillance-like.</item>
        <item>Behaviors already covered by product analytics — diary adds self-report noise without incremental signal.</item>
        <item>Rare events (less than once per week) — participants miss too many triggers to form useful patterns.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="definition-and-types">
      <p>A diary study is a longitudinal research method where participants record experiences, behaviors, and thoughts in the moment or shortly after, over an extended period. It captures real-world context that lab studies erase and reveals how behavior evolves over time.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Choose the study type based on what triggers a relevant event for your research question.</statement>
        <rationale>Each type captures different behavioral signals. Mixing types within one study produces incommensurable data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Interval-contingent: entries at fixed times (daily, weekly) — for routine behaviors and scheduled usage.</item>
        <item>Event-contingent: entries when a specific event occurs — for specific interactions and triggered behaviors.</item>
        <item>Signal-contingent: entries on random prompts — for capturing natural moments without scheduling bias.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="design-decisions">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap study duration at 10-21 days for most products; 28+ days only for true habit-formation research.</statement>
        <rationale>Participant fatigue causes 30-50% entry dropout after day 10 in studies without strong re-engagement. Studies longer than 3 weeks lose late entries to "same as yesterday" responses.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Each diary entry must take under 3 minutes to complete. If the form is longer, split into a quick log and a weekly deep-dive.</statement>
        <rationale>Entry burden is the top predictor of dropout. Participants with demanding forms disengage before the study reaches the habit-formation window.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Duration: days, weeks, or months depending on the behavior under study.</item>
        <item>Frequency: daily, event-based, or random signal.</item>
        <item>Format: dedicated app, SMS, email, paper — choose based on participant tech comfort.</item>
        <item>Entry format: text, photo, video, rating — mix modalities for richer corpora.</item>
        <item>Questions: structured (faster to complete) or open (richer but harder to synthesize).</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="planning-steps">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define research questions before selecting study type or duration. The questions determine whether a diary study is the right method at all.</statement>
        <rationale>Diary studies answer temporal and contextual questions. Using them for questions better answered by interviews or analytics wastes 2-4 weeks of participant effort.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the five-field entry structure for every study: When (date/time), Where (location/context), What (what happened), How (emotional state), Why (participant's interpretation).</statement>
        <rationale>These five fields capture the complete context needed for temporal and contextual analysis. Omitting "Why" produces entries that describe events without meaning; omitting "Where" prevents contextual pattern analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Screen participants for willingness to self-document consistently, not just availability. Participants who journal regularly complete studies at 2x the rate of those who do not.</statement>
        <rationale>The biggest predictor of dropout is unfamiliarity with self-documentation. Selection bias from motivated self-reporters is real but acceptable compared to 50% dropout from unscreened participants.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Conduct a live onboarding session with each participant before the diary period starts. Test their understanding of the entry format with a practice entry.</statement>
        <rationale>Participants who submit a practice entry during onboarding complete 40% more entries than those who only read instructions. The practice entry surfaces confusion before it becomes dropout.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Agents run the operational backbone: scheduled prompts, reminder cadence, multimodal entry intake (text + image + audio), per-participant compliance dashboards, and rolling theme synthesis. Humans do recruitment screening, exit interviews, and final interpretation. A coordinator agent manages each cohort: it schedules prompts, ingests entries, transcribes audio/video locally, classifies entry quality (usable / vague / off-topic), nudges low-compliance participants, and produces weekly synthesis snapshots for the researcher.</p>
      <note>Recommended subagents: faion-ux-researcher-agent (owns the protocol, designs entry templates, performs final synthesis); faion-product-manager (converts diary themes into opportunity statements + roadmap signals); faion-content-marketer (extracts user-language vocabulary surfacing in entries); faion-llm-integration (operationalizes multimodal ingestion with Whisper transcription, image captioning); faion-data-analyst style subagent (computes compliance and engagement metrics per participant).</note>
    </section>
    <section name="synthesis-patterns">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use rolling synthesis, not batch analysis. Run a theme-synthesis pass weekly from day 3 so emerging patterns can generate follow-up questions while participants are still active.</statement>
        <rationale>Late synthesis produces a complete retrospective analysis of an unprobed dataset. Themes identified by day 7 become the raw material for exit interview questions on day 14.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Participant fatigue: dropoff after day 7-10 unless re-engaged. Studies &gt;3 weeks lose 30-50% of entries.</statement>
        <rationale>Study duration and entry format directly impact completion. Shorter, lighter studies with multimodal options yield richer datasets than longer, text-heavy ones.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Selection bias: people willing to journal twice daily for a month are not your average user.</statement>
        <rationale>Screen for journaling comfort and consistency as a research variable, not a bug. Acknowledge selection bias in findings interpretation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Self-report drift: entries early in the study are detailed; late entries become "same as yesterday".</statement>
        <rationale>Quality metrics like entry length and detail are signals of engagement and thoroughness. Weight late entries lower or re-engage participants at mid-study.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Recall bias on event-contingent prompts: "log every time you used the app" → users batch-log at end of day, losing in-the-moment context.</statement>
        <rationale>Immediate prompts (push notifications, random signal-contingent) reduce recall drift. Trade-off: more interruption for better fidelity. Choose based on research question priorities.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap the study at 10-21 days for most products; 28+ days only for true habit-formation research.</statement>
        <rationale>Longer studies add data overhead without proportional insight gain. Study duration should match research question temporal scope.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Send mid-study check-in calls (15 min) to catch confusion and rebuild commitment. This single intervention lifts compliance noticeably.</statement>
        <rationale>Human contact mid-study signals that effort matters and gives participants a chance to clarify confusion before they disengage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pay in tranches: e.g. 30% on completion of week 1, 70% at study end. Pre-paid full incentive correlates with mid-study dropout.</statement>
        <rationale>Incentive structure shapes completion. Staged incentives maintain commitment through the middle slump.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Mix entry formats: text + photo + 30-sec voice. Different participants engage with different modalities; mixed corpora are richer for synthesis.</statement>
        <rationale>Multimodal intake captures context that single-modality studies miss (visual environments, vocal tone, emotional state).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always conclude with an exit interview (30-45 min) per participant; the diary entries become the interview script.</statement>
        <rationale>Exit interviews validate diary findings, surface misinterpretations, and provide narrative context for quantitative patterns.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Voice entries with PII (addresses, names, financial info) transcribed to cloud LLM without local processing first.</description>
        <reason>Transcribe locally (Whisper) before any cloud LLM step. dscout and similar SaaS hold raw audio — verify data residency before uploading.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM theme synthesis over-clusters early entries; agent flattens evolution across the study.</description>
        <reason>Force per-week themes and require the model to surface "themes that emerged this week vs prior weeks" so evolution isn't flattened.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Vision models miss the actual subject when captioning image entries.</description>
        <reason>Pair vision caption with the participant's text caption — never rely on the vision model alone.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Reminder fatigue: automated nudges feel spammy after the third unanswered prompt.</description>
        <reason>Switch to a single human-style check-in DM after two missed days, or adjust entry expectations with the participant.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Compliance metrics ("X entries received") hide entry quality.</description>
        <reason>Run a quality classifier and report "usable entries" separately. Flag entries that are vague, off-topic, or repetitive.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent autonomously decides to extend the study or ask additional questions mid-study.</description>
        <reason>Protocol changes mid-study invalidate cross-participant comparison and need researcher approval. Agents should flag themes but not modify protocol.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/study-plan.md" purpose="Full study plan skeleton: research questions, participants, design, diary entry structure, timeline, engagement plan."/>
      <template path="templates/entry-daily.md" purpose="Daily diary entry template with location, rating, problems, surprises fields."/>
      <template path="templates/entry-event.md" purpose="Event-contingent entry template: trigger, goal, outcome, rating, optional photo."/>
      <template path="templates/diary-bot.py" purpose="Minimal Telegram-bot intake skeleton for text + photo + voice entries → JSONL."/>
    </templates>
